# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ene
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ene/al] In chemistry, the suffix **-al** is the IUPAC nomenclature used in organic chemistry to form names of aldehydes containing the -(CO)H group in the systematic form.
[src:ene/al] It was extracted from the word "aldehyde".
[src:ene/al] With the exception of chemical compounds having a higher priority than it, all aldehydes are named using -al, such as 'propanal'.
[src:ene/al] Some aldehydes also have common names, such as formaldehyde for methanal, acetaldehyde for ethanal.
[src:ene/al] Benzaldehyde does not have a systematic form with -al.
[src:ene/ane] In organic chemistry, the suffix ***-ane*** forms the names of organic compounds where the −C−C− group (a carbon-carbon single bond) has been attributed the highest priority according to the rules of organic nomenclature.
[src:ene/ane] Such organic compounds are called *alkanes*.
[src:ene/ane] The names of the saturated hydrides of non-metals end with the suffix ***-ane***: the hydrides of silicon are called silanes (SiH4); the hydrides of boron are boranes (B2H6).
[src:ene/ane] The final "*-e*" is dropped before a suffix that starts with a vowel, e.g.
[src:ene/ane] Alternatively, "*-ane*" may be used for a mononuclear hydride of an element.
[src:ene/ane] For instance, methane for CH4 and oxidane for H2O (water).
[src:ene/ase] The suffix **-ase** is used in biochemistry to form names of enzymes.
[src:ene/ase] The most common way to name enzymes is to add this suffix onto the end of the substrate, *e.g.* an enzyme that breaks down peroxides may be called peroxidase; the enzyme that produces telomeres is called telomerase.
[src:ene/ase] Sometimes enzymes are named for the function they perform, rather than substrate, e.g. the enzyme that polymerizes (assembles) DNA into strands is called polymerase; see also reverse transcriptase.
[src:ene/ase] The *-ase* suffix is a libfix derived from "diastase", the first recognized enzyme.
[src:ene/ase] Its usage in subsequently discovered enzymes was proposed by Émile Duclaux, with the intention of honoring the first scientists to isolate diastase.
[src:ene/ene] The suffix **-ene** is used in organic chemistry to form names of organic compounds where the -C=C- group has been attributed the highest priority according to the rules of organic nomenclature.
[src:ene/ene] Sometimes a number between hyphens is inserted before it to say that the double bond is between that atom and the atom with the next number up.
[src:ene/ene] This suffix is taken from the end of the word ethylene, which is the simplest alkene.
[src:ene/ene] The final "-e" disappears if it is followed by a suffix that starts with a vowel, e.g.
[src:ene/ene] "-enal" which is a compound that contains both a -C=C- bond and an aldehyde functional group.
[src:ene/ene] A Greek number prefix before the "-ene" indicates how many double bonds there are in the compound, e.g. butadiene.
[src:ene/ene] The suffix "-ene" is also used in inorganic chemistry to indicate a one-atom thick two-dimensional layer of atoms—known as a "Xene"—as in graphene, silicene, stanene, borophene, and germanene.
[src:ene/ene] Additionally, the suffixis used for MXenes due to their similarity to graphene.
[src:ene/ine] *asinine, canine, feline, ursine*), the suffix is usually pronounced /aɪn/ or in some words alternatively /ɪn/.
[src:ene/ine] *Levantine, Byzantine, Argentine*) it is usually /aɪn/ or /iːn/.
[src:ene/ine] But in chemistry, it is usually pronounced /iːn/ or /ɪn/ depending on the word it appears in and the accent of the speaker.
[src:ene/ine] In a few words (for example, *quinine*, *iodine* and *strychnine*), the /aɪn/ sound is normal in some accents.
[src:ene/ine] *Gasoline* ends with /iːn/; *glycerine* more often with /ɪn/ than with /iːn/.
[src:ene/ine] In *caffeine*, the suffix has merged with the *e* in the root, for stressed /ˈiːn/; in *gasoline* and *margarine* as well the suffix is stressed by some people.
[src:ene/ine] Some elements of the periodic table (namely the halogens, in the Group 17) have this suffix: fluorine (F), chlorine (Cl), bromine (Br), iodine (I) and astatine (At), ending which was continued in the artificially created tennessine (Ts).
[src:ene/ine] The suffix *-in* (/ɪn/) is etymologically related and overlaps in usage with *-ine*.
[src:ene/ine] Many proteins and lipids have names ending with *-in*: for example, the enzymes pepsin and trypsin, the hormones insulin and gastrin, and the lipids stearin (stearine) and olein.
[src:ene/oate] The suffix **-oate** is the IUPAC nomenclature used in organic chemistry to form names of compounds formed with ester.
[src:ene/oate] The most common examples of compounds named with the "oate" suffix are esters, like ethyl acetate, CH 3COOCH 2CH 3.
[src:ene/oic-acid] In organic chemistry, a **carboxylic acid** is a polar, organic acid that contains a **carboxyl group** (−C(=O)−OH) attached to an R-group.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The general formula of a carboxylic acid is often written as **R−COOH** or **R−CO2H**, sometimes as R−C(O)OH, with R referring to an organyl group (e.g., alkyl, alkenyl, aryl), or hydrogen, or other groups.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Important examples include the amino acids and fatty acids.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Deprotonation of a carboxylic acid gives a carboxylate anion.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are often considered weak acids as they only partially ionise (dissociate) in water.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are commonly identified by their trivial names.
[src:ene/oic-acid] IUPAC-recommended names also exist; in this system, carboxylic acids have an *-oic acid* suffix.
[src:ene/oic-acid] For example, butyric acid (CH3CH2CH2CO2H) is butanoic acid by IUPAC guidelines.
[src:ene/oic-acid] For nomenclature of complex molecules containing a carboxylic acid, the carboxyl can be considered position one of the parent chain even if there are other substituents, such as 3-chloropropanoic acid.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Alternately, it can be named as a "carboxy" or "carboxylic acid" substituent on another parent structure, such as 2-carboxyfuran.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The carboxylate anion (R−COO− or R−CO−2) of a carboxylic acid is usually named with the suffix *-ate*, in keeping with the general pattern of *-ic acid* and *-ate* for a conjugate acid and its conjugate base, respectively.
[src:ene/oic-acid] For example, the conjugate base of acetic acid is acetate.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carbonic acid, which occurs in bicarbonate buffer systems in nature, is not generally classed as one of the carboxylic acids, despite it having a moiety that looks like a COOH group.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Because they are both hydrogen-bond acceptors (the carbonyl −C(=O)−) and hydrogen-bond donors (the hydroxyl −OH), they also participate in hydrogen bonding.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Together, the hydroxyl and carbonyl group form the functional group carboxyl.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids usually exist as dimers in nonpolar media due to their tendency to "self-associate".
[src:ene/oic-acid] Smaller carboxylic acids (1 to 5 carbons) are soluble in water, whereas bigger carboxylic acids have limited solubility due to the increasing hydrophobic nature of the alkyl chain.
[src:ene/oic-acid] These longer chain acids tend to be soluble in less-polar solvents such as ethers and alcohols.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Aqueous sodium hydroxide and carboxylic acids, even hydrophobic ones, react to yield water-soluble sodium salts.
[src:ene/oic-acid] For example, enanthic acid has a low solubility in water (0.2 g/L), but its sodium salt is very soluble in water.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids tend to have higher boiling points than water, because of their greater surface areas and their tendency to form stabilized dimers through hydrogen bonds.
[src:ene/oic-acid] For boiling to occur, either the dimer bonds must be broken or the entire dimer arrangement must be vaporized, increasing the enthalpy of vaporization requirements significantly.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are Brønsted–Lowry acids because they are proton (H+) donors.
[src:ene/oic-acid] They are the most common type of organic acid.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are typically weak acids, meaning that they only partially dissociate into [H3O]+ cations and R−CO−2 anions in neutral aqueous solution.
[src:ene/oic-acid] For example, at room temperature, in a 1-molar solution of acetic acid, only 0.001% of the acid are dissociated (i.e.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Electron-withdrawing substituents such as trifluoromethyl (−CF3) give stronger acids (the p*K*a of acetic acid is 4.76 whereas trifluoroacetic acid, with a trifluoromethyl substituent, has a p*K*a of 0.23).
[src:ene/oic-acid] Deprotonation of carboxylic acids gives carboxylate anions; these are resonance stabilized, because the negative charge is delocalized over the two oxygen atoms, increasing the stability of the anion.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Each of the carbon–oxygen bonds in the carboxylate anion has a partial double-bond character.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The carbonyl carbon's partial positive charge is also weakened by the −1/2 negative charges on the 2 oxygen atoms.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids often have strong sour odours.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Esters of carboxylic acids tend to have fruity, pleasant odours, and many are used in perfume.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are readily identified as such by infrared spectroscopy.
[src:ene/oic-acid] They exhibit a sharp band associated with vibration of the C=O carbonyl bond (*ν*C=O) between 1680 and 1725 cm−1.
[src:ene/oic-acid] A characteristic *ν*O–H band appears as a broad peak in the 2500 to 3000 cm−1 region.
[src:ene/oic-acid] By 1H NMR spectrometry, the hydroxyl hydrogen appears in the 10–13 ppm region, although it is often either broadened or not observed owing to exchange with traces of water.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Many carboxylic acids are produced industrially on a large scale.
[src:ene/oic-acid] They are also frequently found in nature.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Esters of fatty acids are the main components of lipids and polyamides of aminocarboxylic acids are the main components of proteins.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids are used in the production of polymers, pharmaceuticals, solvents, and food additives.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase (aka RuBisCo), the most abundant protein, catalyzes the carbonation to give carboxylic acids.
[src:ene/oic-acid] This conversion is the carbon-fixation step in photosynthesis.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Routes to other biologically prevalent carboxylic acids - citric, oxalic, amino acids, etc. - entail hydrolysis of thioesters and phosphate esters.
[src:ene/oic-acid] In contrast to methods used on a laboratory scale, industrial routes to carboxylic acids often require specialized equipment for high pressures and high temperatures.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Preparative methods for small scale reactions for research or for production of fine chemicals often employ expensive consumable reagents.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Many reactions produce carboxylic acids but are used only in specific cases or are mainly of academic interest.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids react with bases to form carboxylate salts, in which the hydrogen of the hydroxyl (–OH) group is replaced with a metal cation.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Widely practiced reactions convert carboxylic acids into esters, amides, carboxylate salts, acid chlorides, and alcohols.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Their conversion to esters is widely used, e.g. in the production of polyesters.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Likewise, carboxylic acids are converted into amides, but this conversion typically does not occur by direct reaction of the carboxylic acid and the amine.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Instead esters are typical precursors to amides.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The conversion of amino acids into peptides is a significant biochemical process that requires ATP.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Converting a carboxylic acid to an amide is possible, but not straightforward.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Instead of acting as a nucleophile, an amine will react as a base in the presence of a carboxylic acid to give the ammonium carboxylate salt.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Heating the salt to above 100 °C will drive off water and lead to the formation of the amide.
[src:ene/oic-acid] This method of synthesizing amides is industrially important, and has laboratory applications as well.
[src:ene/oic-acid] In the presence of a strong acid catalyst, carboxylic acids can condense to form acid anhydrides.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The condensation produces water, however, which can hydrolyze the anhydride back to the starting carboxylic acids.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Thus, the formation of the anhydride via condensation is an equilibrium process.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Under acid-catalyzed conditions, carboxylic acids will react with alcohols to form esters via the Fischer esterification reaction, which is also an equilibrium process.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Alternatively, diazomethane can be used to convert an acid to an ester.
[src:ene/oic-acid] While esterification reactions with diazomethane often give quantitative yields, diazomethane is only useful for forming methyl esters.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Like esters, most carboxylic acids can be reduced to alcohols by hydrogenation, or using hydride transferring agents such as lithium aluminium hydride.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Strong alkyl transferring agents, such as organolithium compounds but not Grignard reagents, will reduce carboxylic acids to ketones along with transfer of the alkyl group.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The Vilsmaier reagent (*N*,*N*-Dimethyl(chloromethylene)ammonium chloride; [ClHC=N+(CH3)2]Cl−) is a highly chemoselective agent for carboxylic acid reduction.
[src:ene/oic-acid] It selectively activates the carboxylic acid to give the carboxymethyleneammonium salt, which can be reduced by a mild reductant like lithium tris(*t*-butoxy)aluminum hydride to afford an aldehyde in a one pot procedure.
[src:ene/oic-acid] This procedure is known to tolerate reactive carbonyl functionalities such as ketone as well as moderately reactive ester, olefin, nitrile, and halide moieties.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The hydroxyl group on carboxylic acids may be replaced with a chlorine atom using thionyl chloride to give acyl chlorides.
[src:ene/oic-acid] In nature, carboxylic acids are converted to thioesters.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Thionyl chloride can be used to convert carboxylic acids to their corresponding acyl chlorides.
[src:ene/oic-acid] First, carboxylic acid **1** attacks thionyl chloride, and chloride ion leaves.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The resulting oxonium ion **2** is activated towards nucleophilic attack and has a good leaving group, setting it apart from a normal carboxylic acid.
[src:ene/oic-acid] In the next step, **2** is attacked by chloride ion to give tetrahedral intermediate **3**, a chlorosulfite.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The tetrahedral intermediate collapses with the loss of sulfur dioxide and chloride ion, giving protonated acyl chloride **4**.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Chloride ion can remove the proton on the carbonyl group, giving the acyl chloride **5** with a loss of HCl.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Phosphorus(III) chloride (PCl3) and phosphorus(V) chloride (PCl5) will also convert carboxylic acids to acid chlorides, by a similar mechanism.
[src:ene/oic-acid] One equivalent of PCl3 can react with three equivalents of acid, producing one equivalent of H3PO3, or phosphorus acid, in addition to the desired acid chloride.
[src:ene/oic-acid] PCl5 reacts with carboxylic acids in a 1:1 ratio, and produces phosphorus(V) oxychloride (POCl3) and hydrogen chloride (HCl) as byproducts.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Carboxylic acids react with Grignard reagents and organolithiums to form ketones.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The first equivalent of nucleophile acts as a base and deprotonates the acid.
[src:ene/oic-acid] A second equivalent will attack the carbonyl group to create a geminal alkoxide dianion, which is protonated upon workup to give the hydrate of a ketone.
[src:ene/oic-acid] Because most ketone hydrates are unstable relative to their corresponding ketones, the equilibrium between the two is shifted heavily in favor of the ketone.
[src:ene/oic-acid] For example, the equilibrium constant for the formation of acetone hydrate from acetone is only 0.002.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The carboxylic group is the most acidic in organic compounds.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The carboxyl radical, •COOH, only exists briefly.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The acid dissociation constant of •COOH has been measured using electron paramagnetic resonance spectroscopy.
[src:ene/oic-acid] The carboxyl group tends to dimerise to form oxalic acid.
[src:ene/ol] The suffix **–ol** is used in organic chemistry principally to form names of organic compounds containing the hydroxyl (–OH) group, mainly alcohols.
[src:ene/ol] The suffix was extracted from the word *alcohol*.
[src:ene/ol] The suffix also appears in some trivial names with reference to oils (from Latin *oleum*, oil).
[src:ene/ol] Examples of this sense of the suffix include phenol, eugenol, urushiol, and menthol.
[src:ene/ol] Identify the hydroxyl group and which carbon it is on.
[src:ene/ol] To be alcohol, the -OH must be bonded to a carbon.
[src:ene/ol] Use the suffix -ol to denote which carbon the alcohol group is on.
[src:ene/ol] A three-carbon chain with the -OH on the second carbon would be propan-2-ol.
[src:ene/ol] Note that in some instances, common names are better.
[src:ene/ol] If the -OH is on the end of the chain, or the carbon chain is only 1 or 2, use no number.
[src:ene/ol] Use standard Greek prefixes to name molecules with two or more -OH groups (di- for 2, and so on).
